    <section class="section" id="security">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number">03</span>
        <h2>Security — Critical Findings</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Critical — SEC-01</span>
        <div class="finding-title">Ozow Webhook Has No Signature Verification</div>
        <p>The Ozow webhook handler processes payment confirmations and queues VALR conversions without verifying the request is genuinely from Ozow. Any actor with knowledge of the endpoint URL can POST a fake <code>Status: Complete</code> payload and trigger USDC conversion for a batch they never paid for.</p>
        <p>Ozow signs webhooks with a SHA-512 hash (combining SiteCode, Amount, TransactionReference, and PrivateKey). This must be verified before processing any status update.</p>
<pre class="bad">// Current — VULNERABLE
router.post('/ozow', async (req, res) => {
  const { Status, TransactionReference, Amount, HashCheck } = req.body;
  res.status(200).send('OK');
  if (Status !== 'Complete') return;
  // ... queues VALR conversion — no auth check!</pre>

<pre class="good">// Fix — Verify Ozow hash before processing
const crypto = require('crypto');
function verifyOzowHash(body) {
  const { SiteCode, Amount, Status, TransactionReference,
          IsTest, HashCheck } = body;
  const input = `${SiteCode}${Amount}${Status}${TransactionReference}${IsTest}${process.env.OZOW_PRIVATE_KEY}`;
  const hash = crypto.createHash('sha512').update(input.toLowerCase()).digest('hex');
  return hash === HashCheck?.toLowerCase();
}

router.post('/ozow', async (req, res) => {
  if (!verifyOzowHash(req.body)) {
    logger.warn('Ozow webhook: invalid hash', req.body);
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid hash');
  }
  res.status(200).send('OK');
  // ... safe to process
});</pre>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/webhooks.js · line 38</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Critical — SEC-02</span>
        <div class="finding-title">Fuel Voucher Ownership Not Validated on Unlock</div>
        <p>The <code>POST /vouchers/:id/unlock</code> route fetches the voucher by ID but never checks that the requesting user owns it. Any authenticated user can unlock any other user's voucher if they know or can guess the UUID.</p>
<pre class="bad">// Current — fetches by ID only
const result = await db.query(
  'SELECT * FROM fuel_vouchers WHERE id = $1', [voucherId]);</pre>
<pre class="good">// Fix — join through driver profile to enforce ownership
const result = await db.query(`
  SELECT fv.* FROM fuel_vouchers fv
  JOIN easyfuel_drivers ed ON ed.id = fv.driver_id
  WHERE fv.id = $1 AND ed.user_id = $2
`, [voucherId, req.user.id]);</pre>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/easyfuel.js · POST /vouchers/:id/unlock</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Critical — SEC-03</span>
        <div class="finding-title">User-Controlled clip_percent in SafeBet Deposit</div>
        <p>The SafeBet deposit endpoint accepts <code>bet_savings_pct</code> from the user request body and validates it only as a float between 7 and 10. However, this value is stored and used directly in financial calculations. A malformed client could send a value like <code>7.999...</code> that passes validation but produces unexpected clip amounts. More concerning: the business documentation states the clip rate is decided by the platform (7–10% based on user profile), not user-selectable. This should be a server-determined value, not a client input.</p>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/safebet.js · POST /deposit · line 28</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Critical — SEC-04</span>
        <div class="finding-title">SSH Keys in Version-Controlled Files</div>
        <p>Two public SSH keys (<code>id_rsa.pub</code>, <code>id_rsa_1764457734.pub</code>) are included in the project repository. While these are public keys (not private), their presence in a shared repo reveals the key fingerprints used for server access, and the accompanying private keys may exist in nearby directories. More critically, this pattern suggests the developer habit of keeping SSH material near project files — if a private key ever lands in the repo it would be catastrophic. Move all SSH key management to a dedicated secrets store (AWS Secrets Manager / SSM Parameter Store) and add <code>*.pem *.key id_rsa*</code> to <code>.gitignore</code>.</p>
        <div class="finding-file">id_rsa (1).pub · id_rsa.1764457734 (1).pub</div>
      </div>

      <h3>Additional Security Notes</h3>

      <div class="finding warning">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-warning">Warning — SEC-05</span>
        <div class="finding-title">Geo-Lock Accepts Client-Provided Coordinates Without Verification</div>
        <p>The geo-lock check in <code>/vouchers/:id/unlock</code> uses <code>user_lat</code> and <code>user_lng</code> from the request body without any server-side verification. A determined user can trivially spoof their location by sending the station's coordinates directly. Consider requiring a signed GPS attestation from the mobile SDK (e.g., using device-signed location payloads from Android SafetyNet / iOS DeviceCheck), or combining GPS with network IP geolocation as a secondary signal.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="finding warning">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-warning">Warning — SEC-06</span>
        <div class="finding-title">PayFast ITN: Respond 200 Before Signature Verification</div>
        <p>The PayFast webhook handler sends <code>res.status(200).send('OK')</code> before verifying the PayFast signature — this is actually intentional per PayFast's requirements (they require an immediate 200 before processing). However the code then performs the signature check and silently returns without logging if it fails. Failed signature checks should be logged with full payload for fraud investigation.</p>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/webhooks.js · POST /payfast</div>
      </div>
