      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Bug — FIN-01</span>
        <div class="finding-title">FuelFlex Business Logic Hardcoded, Not Price-Fed</div>
        <p>The FuelFlex <code>/fuelflex/apply</code> endpoint hardcodes <code>totalTankValueCents = 120000</code> (R1,200) as a comment says <em>"For demo: use R1,200 as full tank example"</em>. In production this would issue contracts at a static price regardless of the live fuel price, meaning users sign up for R1,200 during an R1,400 fuel market or overpay during a R1,000 market. The system prompt in <code>brain.ts</code> and the engineering spec both describe dynamic pricing from a fuel price API. This needs to be wired up before launch.</p>
<pre class="bad">// Hardcoded demo value — will cause financial errors in production
const totalTankValueCents = 120000; // R1,200
const depositCents = Math.round(totalTankValueCents / 3); // R400</pre>
<pre class="good">// Correct: pull from fuel price API + use actual tank size from driver profile
const driver = driverResult.rows[0];
const fuelPrice = await getFuelPricePerLitre(station.fuel_type, fuel_type);
const totalTankValueCents = Math.round(fuelPrice * driver.tank_size_litres * 100);
const depositCents = Math.round(totalTankValueCents / 3);</pre>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/easyfuel.js · POST /fuelflex/apply</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Bug — FIN-02</span>
        <div class="finding-title">USDC Rate Hardcoded in SafeBet Brain Calculator</div>
        <p>The <code>computeSafeBetClip()</code> method in <code>brain.ts</code> uses a hardcoded exchange rate of <code>18.5</code> ZAR/USD to estimate USDC acquired. The VALR service correctly fetches live rates via <code>getZARUSDCRate()</code>, but the Brain's calculator — which is used for user-facing financial projections — will show a stale rate. If ZAR weakens significantly (e.g. to 19.5) the brain shows users an overstated USDC estimate.</p>
<pre class="bad">// brain.ts — hardcoded rate
const usdcEstimate = Math.round((clip / 18.5) * 100) / 100;</pre>
<pre class="good">// Pass the live rate from VALR into the brain calculation
const { bid } = await valrService.getZARUSDCRate();
const usdcEstimate = Math.round((clip / bid) * 100) / 100;</pre>
        <div class="finding-file">ai-orchestrator/brain.ts · computeSafeBetClip()</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding critical">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-critical">Bug — FIN-03</span>
        <div class="finding-title">EFT Fee Calculation Applied Twice</div>
        <p>In the EFT disbursement worker, the platform fee is calculated and then applied inconsistently. The wallet is debited by <code>amount_cents + feeCents</code>, but the ledger entry also records <code>amount_cents + feeCents</code> as the debit amount. The disbursement sent via PayFast is <code>netCents = amount_cents - feeCents</code>. This means the user is debited <em>amount + fee</em> but only receives <em>amount - fee</em> — the user's account is charged the fee twice (once as a deduction from the disbursed amount, once as an explicit debit).</p>
<pre class="bad">// worker.js — double-charging the fee
const feeCents = Math.round(amount_cents * 0.01); // 1%
const netCents = amount_cents - feeCents;
// Wallet debit: amount_cents + feeCents  (user pays full amount + fee)
// PayFast disburse: netCents = amount - fee  (user receives less than they intended)
// Net effect: user is short by 2x the fee</pre>
<pre class="good">// Correct: debit only amount_cents from wallet; fee comes out of the disbursement
const feeCents = Math.round(amount_cents * 0.01);
const netCents = amount_cents - feeCents;
// Wallet debit: amount_cents only
// PayFast disburse: netCents
// Separately credit feeCents to a platform fee ledger account</pre>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/jobs/worker.js · eftWorker</div>
      </div>

