        <li class="check-warn">No rate limit on <code>/vouchers/:id/unlock</code> — brute-forcing voucher IDs (UUIDs) is infeasible but the endpoint should still be rate-limited per user</li>
        <li class="check-warn">FuelFlex 3.5% service fee (<code>serviceFeeCents = Math.round(totalTankValueCents * 0.035)</code>) is not shown to the user in a FSCA-compliant cost disclosure</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- SAFEBET -->
    <section class="section" id="safebet">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number">09</span>
        <h2>SafeBet</h2>
      </div>

      <p>SafeBet has the most complex payment pipeline and is generally well-implemented. The idempotency key, BullMQ async processing, and 3-month/12-month unlock logic are correctly built.</p>

      <ul class="checklist">
        <li class="check-pass">Idempotency key check prevents duplicate deposits</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Batch created in <code>'converting'</code> state before payment — prevents claiming funds before Ozow confirms</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Unlock dates calculated at deposit time and stored — correct</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Withdrawal properly blocked with clear error messages until unlock date</li>
        <li class="check-pass">VALR integration for USDC conversion is correctly async (queued not inline)</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Portfolio view correctly fetches live USDC rate from VALR with fallback</li>
        <li class="check-fail">Ozow hash missing from payment URL (PAY-02 above)</li>
        <li class="check-fail">User controls clip percentage — should be platform-determined (SEC-03 above)</li>
        <li class="check-warn">No maximum deposit cap — a user depositing R10M would trigger a large automatic USDC buy. Add a daily/monthly deposit cap and an AML review trigger above a threshold (e.g. R50,000/day)</li>
        <li class="check-warn">The Ozow webhook (webhooks.js) updates <code>contribution_batches.status = 'active'</code> at webhook time, but the BullMQ worker also sets status to <code>'active'</code> after VALR conversion. These race and can conflict if the worker processes before the webhook status update completes.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- WORKERS -->
    <section class="section" id="workers">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number">10</span>
        <h2>Async Workers (BullMQ)</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="finding good">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-good">Good</span>
        <div class="finding-title">Idempotent Worker Pattern</div>
        <p>The deposit worker checks <code>if (batch.status === 'active') return;</code> before processing — this correctly makes the worker idempotent so that BullMQ retries don't double-process a VALR conversion. This is the right pattern for financial workers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="finding good">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-good">Good</span>
        <div class="finding-title">FOR UPDATE Locking</div>
        <p>Financial workers use <code>SELECT ... FOR UPDATE</code> to lock rows during processing. This prevents concurrent workers from processing the same batch simultaneously — correct use of PostgreSQL advisory locking within a transaction.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="finding warning">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-warning">Warning</span>
        <div class="finding-title">Worker Queue Name Mismatch</div>
        <p>The SafeBet webhook queues a job to <code>'deposit-split'</code> with the payload key <code>batch_id</code>. The worker listens on <code>'deposit-split'</code> and reads <code>job.data.batch_id</code>. However, the <code>depositQueue</code> in <code>safebet.js</code> is created as <code>new Queue('deposit-split')</code> but withdrawal jobs are added with <code>depositQueue.add('withdrawal', ...)</code>. The worker doesn't have a processor for <code>'withdrawal'</code> job names — these jobs will queue and never process.</p>
        <div class="finding-file">backend/src/routes/safebet.js · POST /withdraw · backend/src/jobs/worker.js</div>
      </div>

      <div class="finding info">
        <span class="finding-badge badge-info">Note</span>
        <div class="finding-title">No Dead Letter Queue or Job Monitoring</div>
        <p>Failed jobs (<code>worker.on('failed')</code>) are only logged to console. In production, failed financial jobs need a dead letter queue with alerting, and a manual review process. Consider adding Bull Dashboard or Grafana + BullMQ metrics for operational visibility into job queues.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- DATABASE -->
    <section class="section" id="database">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number">11</span>
        <h2>Database / Schema</h2>
      </div>

      <ul class="checklist">
        <li class="check-pass">UUID primary keys throughout (no sequential IDs that enumerate users)</li>
        <li class="check-pass">BIGINT cents for all monetary amounts — no FLOAT/DECIMAL money</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Phone format CHECK constraint (<code>+[10-15 digits]</code> E.164)</li>
        <li class="check-pass">PostGIS enabled for merchant geo-point (EasyFuel geo-lock backup)</li>
        <li class="check-pass"><code>wallet_transactions</code> is correctly immutable (INSERT only, no UPDATE)</li>
        <li class="check-pass">KYC records deduplicated per user/provider with UNIQUE constraint</li>
        <li class="check-pass">DB connection pool with <code>connectionTimeoutMillis: 5000</code> prevents pile-up</li>
        <li class="check-pass">SSL enforcement in production via <code>ssl.rejectUnauthorized: true</code></li>
        <li class="check-warn">Two schema files exist: <code>infra/postgres/schema.sql</code> and <code>database/schema.sql</code> — verify they are in sync</li>
        <li class="check-warn">No migration framework (Flyway/db-migrate/Knex) — manual schema changes in production are risky</li>
        <li class="check-warn"><code>DB_SSL_CERT</code> is required for RDS SSL but is not in <code>.env.example</code> — easy to miss during deployment</li>
        <li class="check-na">Read replicas not configured — add for Brain telemetry queries to avoid read load on primary</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- INFRASTRUCTURE -->
    <section class="section" id="infra">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number">12</span>
        <h2>Infrastructure</h2>
      </div>

      <ul class="checklist">
        <li class="check-pass">TLS 1.2/1.3 only, HSTS with preload, OCSP stapling in Nginx</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Route-level rate limiting: 10/min auth, 30/min API, 60/min webhooks</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Server tokens hidden (<code>server_tokens off</code>)</li>
        <li class="check-pass">PM2 multi-process management with separate API and Brain processes</li>
        <li class="check-pass">90-second Brain proxy timeout accommodates Claude API latency</li>
        <li class="check-pass">EC2 Ubuntu 22.04 LTS — long-term supported, appropriate for production</li>
        <li class="check-pass">Certbot auto-renewal configured</li>
        <li class="check-warn">Single EC2 instance — no Auto Scaling Group. A single instance failure means full platform outage. Consider an ALB + ASG or at minimum a hot standby.</li>
        <li class="check-warn">Webhook endpoints should whitelist Nedbank/Ozow/PayFast IP ranges at Nginx level (in addition to signature verification)</li>
        <li class="check-warn">No CloudWatch/APM monitoring configured in setup.sh — add before launch</li>
        <li class="check-na">Redis on localhost — single node. For production resilience, use ElastiCache cluster with replication</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

